`crates/ctx-cage/src/lifecycle/` implements the full prepareâ†’runâ†’teardown pipeline for one cage invocation, exposed as the single `execute(r: &Resolved) -> Result<i32, CageError>` entry point in `mod.rs`. Depending on this module gets you the whole sandboxed-run lifecycle; callers never touch `Prep`, bind lists, or bwrap argv construction directly.

The phases share the `Prep` struct minted by `prepare.rs` (rundir, claude runtime, mask/rules files) and consumed by `run.rs`/`serve.rs` (binds/env via `env.rs`) and finally `teardown.rs`, which deletes exactly `prep.rundir` and nothing else. Teardown always runs, even on failure, and its errors are swallowed â€” only `prepare`/`run` errors propagate to `execute`'s caller. `run.rs` and `serve.rs` are two alternate phase-2 entry points (billed API-proxy-backed exec vs. broker-backed exec for tool calls); a given `Resolved`/`Mode` drives exactly one of them, and both build their `bwrap` config from the same `env.rs` bind/env resolution and `Prep`.

Two cross-cutting invariants constrain edits anywhere in this subtree: `target_root` must be canonicalized before binding (bwrap binds it at an identical in-cage path per ADR-046, so a relative path corrupts host mount creation), and billed modes require a clean git tree (`ensure_clean_tree` in `prepare.rs`) because the workspace is mounted read-write and git-commit is the only rollback path. `env.rs`'s tool-dir resolution feeds both the bwrap bind list and PATH construction â€” these two call sites must stay in sync or bind visibility and PATH lookup silently diverge. `run/` (subordinate rollup) owns PTY attachment and relay-wait timing for interactive/billed execs, with a strict ordering invariant (relay-wait, then `setsid --ctty` wrapping, then PTY relay spawn) that any change to command construction must preserve.